"""
mkt-context: Psalms 111-117
Chapters: 111-117 (76 verses total)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-psalms-111-117.py

Key context decisions:
- Ps 111-112: Acrostic diptych; Ps 111 praises YHWH, Ps 112 praises the YHWH-fearer;
  112:3,9 borrows 111:3 phrase "righteousness endures forever" (Paul quotes 112:9 in 2 Cor 9:9)
- Ps 113-118: Egyptian Hallel (sung at Passover); 113-114 before meal, 115-118 after
- Ps 113:7 nearly verbatim from Hannah's Song (1 Sam 2:8); Mary Magnificat trajectory
- Ps 114: vivid personification of Exodus events; sea/Jordan/mountains responding to divine presence
- Ps 115:8: worshipers become like their idols — key OT anthropological point
- Ps 116:10 quoted by Paul in 2 Cor 4:13; "cup of salvation" (v13) = todah sacrifice
- Ps 116:15 "precious in sight of LORD is death of saints" — two interpretive options noted
- Ps 117: Paul cites in Rom 15:11 for Gentile inclusion; shortest chapter, near Bible midpoint
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge without overwriting any verse already present in existing
    # CHANGE? Do not alter the guard; concurrent agents depend on append-only behavior
    # VERIFY: run twice; second run should report identical byte count for psalms.json
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {"111": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 111: Acrostic Praise of YHWH's Covenant Works — Companion to Ps 112.</b> Ps 111 is an acrostic psalm: each of the 22 half-lines begins with successive Hebrew letters (Aleph to Taw). The structural correspondence with Ps 112 is intentional — Ps 111 praises YHWH's works; Ps 112 (identical structure, same vocabulary) praises the one who fears YHWH, showing that the character of YHWH is reproduced in those who fear him. Together they form a diptych. 'I will give thanks to the LORD with my whole heart, in the company of the upright, in the congregation' (<i>odeh YHWH bechol levav besod yesharim veaedah</i>) — the praise is explicitly corporate: in the 'council of the upright' (<i>sod yesharim</i>, the intimate circle of the righteous) and in the 'congregation' (<i>edah</i>, the assembly). Private devotion leads to public praise.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Great are the works of the LORD, studied by all who delight in them'</b> — 'great are the works' (<i>gedolim ma'asei YHWH</i>) — the theology of YHWH's works as the primary object of study. 'Studied by all who delight in them' (<i>derushim lechol chephtzeihem</i>) — the verb <i>darash</i> (to seek, inquire, study diligently) is the same root used for 'seeking YHWH' in covenant literature. Delighting in YHWH's works drives their study; the works reward study with deeper delight. This is the epistemology of worship: observation and reflection on what YHWH has done creates the material for praise.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Full of splendor and majesty is his work, and his righteousness endures forever'</b> — 'splendor and majesty' (<i>hod vehadar</i>) — the royal vocabulary of divine glory (Pss 96:6; 104:1; 145:5). 'His righteousness endures forever' (<i>vetzidqato omedet laad</i>) — the first occurrence of this phrase, which appears again at vv9 and 10, and is borrowed for the righteous man of Ps 112:3,9 (2 Cor 9:9 quotes Ps 112:9 in the context of generous giving). The enduring <i>tzedaqah</i> (righteousness) is both God's character and the character imparted to those who fear him.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'He has caused his wondrous works to be remembered; the LORD is gracious and merciful'</b> — 'caused his wondrous works to be remembered' (<i>zeker asah leniphleotav</i>) — YHWH has established a memorial (<i>zeker</i>) for his wondrous works. The Passover and the Sabbath are divine institutions for making the covenant acts memorable. 'Gracious and merciful' (<i>channun verachum YHWH</i>) — the divine self-description from Exod 34:6-7 (the 'Thirteen Attributes': 'the LORD, the LORD, a God merciful and gracious...'). The liturgical formula is quoted throughout the Psalter and prophets to ground petitions in YHWH's revealed character.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'He provides food for those who fear him; he remembers his covenant forever'</b> — 'provides food' (<i>teref natan liyre'av</i> — <i>teref</i>, prey/food, the word for the hunter's catch) — divine provision framed in hunting imagery: YHWH provides the food that his covenant people need. 'Remembers his covenant' (<i>yizkor leolam berito</i>) — covenant memory as the ground of provision. YHWH's provision of manna in the wilderness (Exod 16), of food in the land, and of the sacrificial system's covenant meal are all expressions of this covenantal feeding.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'He has shown his people the power of his works, in giving them the inheritance of the nations'</b> — 'the power of his works' (<i>koach ma'asav</i>) — the power demonstrated in the works is the basis of trust for the future. 'Inheritance of the nations' (<i>nachalat goyim</i>) — the Conquest: YHWH demonstrated his power specifically by displacing the Canaanite nations and giving their land to Israel as an inheritance (<i>nachalah</i>). The Conquest is the primary OT demonstration of divine power after the Exodus.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'The works of his hands are faithful and just; all his precepts are trustworthy'</b> — 'faithful and just' (<i>emet umishpat</i>) — the works are characterized by truth (<i>emet</i>) and justice (<i>mishpat</i>): the same qualities demanded of human judges (Lev 19:15; Deut 16:20). 'His precepts are trustworthy' (<i>piqqudav ne'emanim</i>) — the torah's commands (<i>piqqudim</i>) partake of the same reliability as YHWH's works. What YHWH does and what YHWH commands are both equally dependable.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'They are established forever and ever, to be performed with faithfulness and uprightness'</b> — 'established forever and ever' (<i>semuchim laad leolam</i>) — permanence: the divine precepts and works are not time-bound but eternal. 'Performed with faithfulness and uprightness' (<i>asuyim be-emet veyashar</i>) — YHWH's commands are done in truth and straightforwardness. The divine character guarantees both the permanence of the covenant and the reliability of its terms.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'He sent redemption to his people; he has commanded his covenant forever. Holy and awesome is his name!'</b> — 'sent redemption' (<i>shalach geulah leamo</i>) — the Exodus as the paradigmatic act of redemption. 'His covenant forever' (<i>berito leolam</i>) — the covenant established at Sinai (and ultimately rooted in the Abrahamic covenant) has permanent validity. 'Holy and awesome is his name' (<i>qadosh venora shemo</i>) — the Sinai revelation (Exod 19-20) established YHWH's holiness and the awe it demands. The Name as holy is the reason the Third Commandment prohibits its misuse.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom; a good understanding have all those who practice it. His praise endures forever!'</b> — 'the fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom' (<i>reshit chochmah yir'at YHWH</i>) — the climax of the acrostic and its most famous line; essentially identical with Prov 9:10 ('The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom, and knowledge of the Holy One is understanding'). The <i>reshit</i> (beginning/chief part) of wisdom is not an introductory step to be transcended but the foundational orientation of all human knowing. Wisdom that does not begin with covenant reverence is not biblical wisdom. The acrostic closes with the summary principle that organizes all the preceding praise.</p>"}, "112": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 112: Acrostic of the Blessed God-Fearer — Mirror of Psalm 111.</b> Ps 112 uses the same acrostic structure as Ps 111 (22 half-lines, Aleph to Taw) and deliberately mirrors its language: where Ps 111:3 says 'his righteousness endures forever' of YHWH, Ps 112:3,9 applies the same phrase to the righteous man; where Ps 111:4 says 'gracious and merciful is the LORD,' Ps 112:4 says 'gracious, merciful, and righteous' of the generous person. The theological point: those who fear YHWH come to resemble him. 'Blessed is the man who fears the LORD, who greatly delights in his commandments!' (<i>ashre ish yare YHWH bemitzvotav chaphetz meod</i>) — the beatitude opens the psalm. The fear of YHWH (Ps 111:10, the beginning of wisdom) produces delight in his commandments.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'His offspring will be mighty in the land; the generation of the upright will be blessed'</b> — the blessing extends to descendants: 'mighty in the land' (<i>gibor baaretz</i>) — social, physical, economic strength. 'The generation of the upright will be blessed' (<i>dor yesharim yevorach</i>) — the intergenerational effect of covenant faithfulness. This is the covenant promise structure of Exod 20:6 ('showing steadfast love to thousands of those who love me and keep my commandments').</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Wealth and riches are in his house, and his righteousness endures forever'</b> — 'wealth and riches' (<i>hon vaosher</i>) — material prosperity as covenant blessing (Deut 28:1-14 catalogues such blessings). The linkage of material prosperity and righteousness is the Deuteronomic theology, subject to the test cases of Job and Qohelet. 'His righteousness endures forever' (<i>tzidqato omedet laad</i>) — the exact phrase of Ps 111:3 now applied to the righteous person. Paul quotes this in 2 Cor 9:9 to argue that the righteous giver scatters and gives to the poor — and this endures.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Light dawns in the darkness for the upright; he is gracious, merciful, and righteous'</b> — 'light dawns in the darkness' (<i>zarach bachoshech or layesharim</i>) — the darkness of adversity is where the covenant light appears. 'Gracious, merciful, and righteous' (<i>channun verachum vetzaddiq</i>) — the three divine attributes of Ps 111:4 ('gracious and merciful') now applied to the upright person with 'righteous' added. The blurring of the boundary between divine and human character is the Psalm's theological point: those who fear YHWH take on his attributes.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'It is well with the man who deals generously and lends; who conducts his affairs with justice'</b> — 'deals generously and lends' (<i>tovtov ish chonek umalveh</i>) — the economic ethics of the covenant community: generosity (<i>chanon</i>, showing grace/favor to the poor) and lending without exploitative interest (the OT prohibition on usury within the community: Exod 22:25; Lev 25:35-37; Deut 15:7-11). 'Conducts his affairs with justice' (<i>yekalkel devarav bemishpat</i>) — all economic dealings governed by covenant justice.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'For the righteous will never be moved; he will be remembered forever'</b> — 'never be moved' (<i>lo-yimot leolam</i>) — the covenant security of the righteous: not moved by adversity. 'Remembered forever' (<i>lezecher olam yihyeh</i>) — the permanence of the righteous person's legacy. In the ANE, being 'remembered' after death through one's name and descendants was the primary form of immortality. The righteous person's name endures because YHWH preserves it.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'He is not afraid of bad news; his heart is firm, trusting in the LORD'</b> — 'not afraid of bad news' (<i>mishemu'ah raah lo yira</i>) — the psychological stability of the covenant-trusting person: even when bad reports come, the heart is not destabilized. 'His heart is firm, trusting in the LORD' (<i>nachon libbo batach bYHWH</i>) — the <i>batach</i> (trust, the covenant reliance on YHWH) produces a 'firm' (<i>nachon</i>, established, ready) heart. The correspondence between internal stability and external trust is the Psalm's anthropology.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'His heart is steady; he will not be afraid, until he looks in triumph on his adversaries'</b> — 'steady' (<i>samuch</i>) — the same word as Ps 111:8 ('established/steadfast'), now applied to the human heart. The repetition of 'not afraid' (vv7-8) emphasizes the theme: the double negative reinforces the complete absence of the fear that adversity normally produces. 'Until he looks in triumph on his adversaries' (<i>ad asher yireh betzarav</i>) — the final vindication: the righteous person will live to see the defeat of those who opposed him.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'He has distributed freely; he has given to the poor; his righteousness endures forever; his horn is exalted in honor'</b> — 'distributed freely, given to the poor' (<i>pizar natan laevyonim</i>) — the generous scattering of resources to the needy. Paul quotes this verse in 2 Cor 9:9 as the biblical warrant for generous giving to the Jerusalem collection: the agricultural metaphor of scattering seed (<i>pizar</i>) applied to financial generosity. 'His horn is exalted in honor' (<i>qarno tarum bekhavod</i>) — the horn as the symbol of strength and dignity; exaltation in honor as the divine reward for generosity.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'The wicked man sees it and is angry; he gnashes his teeth and melts away; the desire of the wicked will perish!'</b> — the psalm's final verse pivots to the wicked person's response: rage and dissolution. 'Gnashes his teeth' (<i>shinav yachroq</i>) — the physical expression of frustrated envy. 'Melts away' (<i>venamas</i>) — the wicked person dissolves; his rage has no constructive outlet and consumes him. 'The desire of the wicked will perish' (<i>ta'avat risha'im toved</i>) — the comprehensive reversal: what the wicked person wants (to see the righteous fail) will itself fail. The blessed man of v1 is vindicated by the very contrast the wicked person cannot bear.</p>"}, "113": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 113: Opening of the Egyptian Hallel — Universal Praise, Particular Reversal.</b> Pss 113-118 form the 'Hallel' (Egyptian Hallel or Hallel HaMitzri), sung at the three pilgrimage festivals (Passover, Weeks, Tabernacles). At Passover, Pss 113-114 were sung before the meal and Pss 115-118 after it (the 'hymn' Jesus and the disciples sang in Matt 26:30; Mark 14:26 was likely Pss 115-118). 'Praise the LORD! Praise, O servants of the LORD, praise the name of the LORD!' — the triple imperative of praise (<i>hallelu Yah halelu avdei YHWH halelu et shem YHWH</i>) — the servants of YHWH, his worshiping community, are summoned to praise the divine Name. The Name is what is praised — the character and attributes of YHWH as revealed in covenant history.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Blessed be the name of the LORD from this time forth and forevermore!'</b> — the blessing of the divine Name: <i>yehi shem YHWH mevorach</i> (let the name of the LORD be blessed). 'From this time forth and forevermore' (<i>me'atah vead olam</i>) — temporal universality matching the geographic universality of v3. The blessing spans all time and all space. This verse and v3 together establish the cosmic scope of the worship that the particular community in Jerusalem was conducting.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'From the rising of the sun to its setting, the name of the LORD is to be praised!'</b> — 'from the rising of the sun to its setting' (<i>mimmizrach shemesh ad mevo'o</i>) — east to west: the full geographic sweep of the inhabited world. The prayer that YHWH's name would be praised across all geography is the Psalter's universalism in miniature. Mal 1:11 uses identical language: 'from the rising of the sun to its setting my name will be great among the nations' — the eschatological vision that the Hallel anticipates.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'The LORD is high above all nations, and his glory above the heavens!'</b> — 'high above all nations' (<i>ram al kol goyim YHWH</i>) — political universalism: YHWH's authority exceeds that of every national patron deity. 'His glory above the heavens' (<i>veal hashamayim kevodo</i>) — cosmological universalism: even the heavens, the highest reach of created space, do not contain or define YHWH's glory. The Hallel's praise is not parochial; it addresses the transcendent God of all creation.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Who is like the LORD our God, who is seated on high'</b> — the incomparability question (<i>mi kamohw YHWH Eloheinu</i>) — the rhetorical question expecting no answer. 'Seated on high' (<i>hammagbihi lashevet</i>) — the divine throne elevated beyond all created thrones. The incomparability formula appears throughout OT (Exod 15:11; Pss 35:10; 89:6; Isa 40:18,25) as the foundational theological affirmation: no other being compares to YHWH.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'...who looks far down on the heavens and the earth?'</b> — 'looks far down on the heavens and the earth' (<i>hamashpili lir'ot bashamayim uvaaretz</i>) — the paradox: YHWH must 'stoop down' (<i>shaphal</i>, to humble oneself, to descend) even to look at the heavens. The highest point of creation is below YHWH's vantage. This divine transcendence is not remoteness but the precondition of the radical condescension that follows in vv7-9.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'He raises the poor from the dust and lifts the needy from the ash heap'</b> — the pivot to particular action. The transcendent God of vv4-6 acts specifically for the lowest human beings. 'Raises the poor from the dust' (<i>meqimi meaphar dal</i>) and 'lifts the needy from the ash heap' (<i>meashpot yarim evyon</i>) — this verse is borrowed almost verbatim from Hannah's Song (1 Sam 2:8: 'He raises up the poor from the dust; he lifts the needy from the ash heap'). Hannah's prayer at the birth of Samuel, and the Psalm's echo of it, create a trajectory: the barren woman given a son becomes the type for all divine reversals.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'...to make them sit with princes, with the princes of his people'</b> — 'to make them sit with princes' (<i>lehoshivi im nedivim</i>) — the social reversal: the ash-heap poor seated with the nobles. 'With the princes of his people' (<i>im nedivei amo</i>) — not foreign nobility but Israel's own leadership: the covenant community's highest seats are given to those the world would place lowest. Mary's Magnificat (Luke 1:52: 'he has brought down the mighty from their thrones and exalted those of humble estate') draws on this text through Hannah's song.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'He gives the barren woman a home, making her the joyful mother of children. Praise the LORD!'</b> — the third reversal: barrenness to motherhood. The barren woman (<i>aqeret habbayit</i>, the childless woman of the house) is given a home and made a 'joyful mother of children' (<i>em habanim semecha</i>). The barren-to-fruitful theme runs through the matriarchal narratives: Sarah (Gen 21), Rebekah (Gen 25:21), Rachel (Gen 30:22), and Hannah (1 Sam 1-2). The Hallel psalm closes with the same reversal that Hannah's prayer celebrated — the God who grants children to the barren is the God who raised up the poor from the dust. The 'Hallelujah!' closes the psalm as it opened it.</p>"}, "114": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 114: The Exodus as Cosmic Event — Creation Responding to YHWH's Presence.</b> Ps 114 is one of the most artistically accomplished poems in the Psalter. It recounts the Exodus and the wilderness journey through vivid personification of creation: the sea flees, the Jordan reverses, mountains skip. The key theological move is in v7: 'Tremble, O earth, at the presence of the LORD' — creation's response to divine presence is not just metaphorical but theologically essential: the created order is designed to respond to its creator. 'When Israel went out from Egypt, the house of Jacob from a people of strange language' — the Exodus as the fundamental national event: Israel 'going out' from Egypt (the Passover theme) and from a 'people of strange language' (<i>am lo'ez</i>, a foreign-speaking people). The alien language of Egypt marks the foreignness of the bondage: Israel was not at home there.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Judah became his sanctuary, Israel his dominion'</b> — 'Judah became his sanctuary' (<i>hayetah Yehudah leqodsho</i>) — the establishment of the Davidic-Solomonic temple in Jerusalem as the divine sanctuary. 'Israel his dominion' (<i>Yisrael mamshelotav</i>) — the covenant nation as YHWH's realm of governance. The Exodus produces not merely freedom but a new political-religious reality: Israel as the territory where YHWH's holiness and rule are distinctively present.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'The sea looked and fled; Jordan turned back'</b> — the sea's flight: the Red Sea at the Exodus (Exod 14:21-22). The Jordan's reversal: the crossing into Canaan under Joshua (Josh 3:14-17). The two water-crossings that bracket the wilderness period are telescoped into a single statement. 'Looked and fled' (<i>raah vayanos</i>) — the sea is personified as a sentient being who sees and flees in terror at YHWH's approach. The Jordan 'turned back' (<i>yissov leachor</i>) — reversal of natural flow.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'The mountains skipped like rams, the hills like lambs'</b> — the mountains of Sinai (the theophany of Exod 19): the shaking of the mountain at YHWH's descent is now described as playful skipping (<i>raqad</i>, to leap, skip, dance). 'Like rams' (<i>ke'eilim</i>) and 'like lambs' (<i>kivnei-tzon</i>) — the animal comparisons give the geological event a pastoral, almost whimsical quality. The terror of Exod 19 is reframed through the Hallel's celebratory register: even Sinai's earthquake was an expression of creation's delight at divine presence.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'What ails you, O sea, that you flee? O Jordan, that you turn back?'</b> — the psalmist addresses the elements directly, mocking them with the question 'what ails you?' (<i>mah lecha hayam ki tanus</i>). The rhetorical question assumes the answer is known: the elements flee because of YHWH's presence. The playful tone of the Hallel psalm makes the cosmic reversal approachable: creation's obedience to its maker is presented as almost amusing in its completeness.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'O mountains, that you skip like rams? O hills, like lambs?'</b> — the same rhetorical question extended to the mountains and hills. The repetition creates a poetic symmetry with v4 while reinforcing the point: all the elements of creation — sea, river, mountains, hills — are addressed and found to have the same answer. The answer is in v7.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Tremble, O earth, at the presence of the LORD, at the presence of the God of Jacob'</b> — the answer to the rhetorical questions: all creation trembles at 'the presence of the LORD' (<i>miliphne adon</i>) and 'the presence of the God of Jacob' (<i>miliphne Eloah Yaakov</i>). The 'presence' (<i>panim</i>) of YHWH is the cause of all the natural reversals described. The God of Jacob — the covenant-patriarch who himself experienced divine reversals (from exile to restoration) — is the one whose presence reorganizes the created order.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'...who turns the rock into a pool of water, the flint into a spring of water'</b> — the water-from-rock miracle at Meribah (Exod 17:1-7; Num 20:1-13): the hardest material transformed into the most life-giving. The 'flint' (<i>challamish</i>, the extremely hard flint-rock of the Sinai) becomes a 'spring of water' (<i>lema'ano mayim</i>). This final image recapitulates the whole Hallel psalm's logic: the God who transforms the sea, the Jordan, the mountains, and the hills also transforms the hardest rock into flowing water. Nothing in creation can resist his transforming presence.</p>"}, "115": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 115: Anti-Idol Polemic and the God Who Acts — 'Not to Us, O LORD.'</b> Ps 115 opens with the most radical self-effacing statement in the Psalter: 'Not to us, O LORD, not to us, but to your name give glory.' The glory of YHWH is the psalm's organizing concern, and the contrast between YHWH (who acts, vv3,12-16) and idols (who cannot act, vv4-8) is the rhetorical engine. 'Not to us, O LORD, not to us, but to your name give glory, for the sake of your steadfast love and your faithfulness!' (<i>lo lanu YHWH lo lanu ki leshimcha ten kavod al chasdecha al amitecha</i>) — the double 'not to us' is emphatic: the people disclaim any credit for YHWH's acts. The ground for divine action is YHWH's own <i>chesed</i> and <i>emet</i> — not Israel's merit.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Why should the nations say, Where is their God?'</b> — the nations' taunt: <i>ayeh na Eloheihem</i> (where now is their God?). This is the theodicy question posed by Israel's enemies (also Pss 42:3; 79:10): if YHWH is Israel's God, why is Israel in distress? The question assumes that a god's worth is measured by his people's visible prosperity and power. The psalm responds by inverting the terms: the question reveals not YHWH's absence but the questioners' false theological assumptions.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'Our God is in the heavens; he does all that he pleases'</b> — 'in the heavens' (<i>bashamayim</i>) — the answer to 'where is their God?': in the heavens, above all earthly measurement. 'Does all that he pleases' (<i>kol asher chaphetz asah</i>) — unrestricted divine sovereignty. The contrast with the idols (vv4-8) is immediate: YHWH does whatever he wants; the idols can do nothing at all. The nations' taunt is answered by the assertion of radical divine freedom.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Their idols are silver and gold, the work of human hands'</b> — 'the work of human hands' (<i>ma'aseh yedei adam</i>) — the idol-polemic's core argument: idols are human artifacts, not divine beings. The same argument appears in Isa 40:18-20; 44:9-20; Jer 10:1-16. The silver and gold of the idols are the most valuable human materials — yet they are inert matter shaped by human craftsmen. The very costliness of the materials exposes the absurdity: the most precious human resources employed to create a powerless object.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'They have mouths, but do not speak; eyes, but do not see'</b> — the sensory catalogue of idol-incapacity: mouths without speech, eyes without sight. The idol has the form of the human senses — the senses that covenant relationship with YHWH requires (hearing his word, seeing his works) — but none of the function. The idol's face is a parody of the 'face of YHWH' (<i>panim</i>) that worshipers seek.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'They have ears, but do not hear; noses, but do not smell'</b> — ears without hearing, noses without smelling: the catalogue continues. 'Hearing' (<i>shama</i>) in covenant theology is the fundamental act of covenant responsiveness — the Shema ('hear, O Israel') frames everything. An idol that cannot hear cannot receive a prayer. A nose that cannot smell means the sacrificial offerings are not received: the covenant communication is one-directional and therefore no communication at all.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'They have hands, but do not feel; feet, but do not walk; and they do not make a sound in their throat'</b> — hands without touch, feet without movement, throats without sound: the final sensory failures. The idol cannot act (hands), cannot come (feet), cannot respond (throat). The climactic list reveals the idol as the anti-YHWH: where YHWH hears, speaks, walks with his people (covenant walk-language: Lev 26:12), the idol does none of these.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'Those who make them become like them; so do all who trust in them'</b> — the most devastating point of the idol polemic: worshipers become like their gods. 'Those who make them become like them' (<i>kemothem yihyu oseihem</i>) — the ontological contagion of idolatry. The idol-maker shapes the idol in his own image, but in worshiping it, he shapes himself in the idol's image: deaf, blind, mute, unable to walk. This is the anthropological corollary of the theological point: worship forms the worshiper. To trust in the incapacitated idols is to share their incapacity.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'O Israel, trust in the LORD! He is their help and their shield'</b> — the first of three covenant-community addresses (Israel, v9; house of Aaron, v10; those who fear YHWH, v11). 'Trust in the LORD' (<i>batach bYHWH</i>) — the alternative to idol-trust. 'He is their help and their shield' (<i>ezram umaginam hu</i>) — the two covenant images of divine protection: 'help' (<i>ezer</i>, the same word as Gen 2:18, the 'helper' Adam needed; also the divine title in Ps 121:2) and 'shield' (<i>magen</i>, the divine protection of Gen 15:1).</p>", "10": "<p><b>'O house of Aaron, trust in the LORD! He is their help and their shield'</b> — the priestly guild addressed separately. The 'house of Aaron' (<i>beit Aaron</i>) — the Aaronic priests who serve in the temple. Their trust in YHWH rather than in the temple's ritual apparatus or the political power of their position is the calling. The refrain 'He is their help and their shield' is identical in all three addresses (vv9-11), creating a liturgical unity across the threefold community structure.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'You who fear the LORD, trust in the LORD! He is their help and their shield'</b> — the third address: 'those who fear the LORD' (<i>yir'ei YHWH</i>). This group may include the Gentile God-fearers who attached themselves to Israel's worship — the proselytes and sympathizers present at the pilgrimage festivals. Their inclusion alongside Israel and the priests creates a universal community of YHWH-fearers within the Hallel's context. The threefold invitation to trust mirrors the threefold blessing of vv12-13.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'The LORD has remembered us; he will bless us; he will bless the house of Israel; he will bless the house of Aaron'</b> — 'the LORD has remembered us' (<i>YHWH zecharanu yevarech</i>) — the covenant memory that activates covenant blessing. The threefold blessing corresponds to the threefold address (Israel, Aaron, those who fear YHWH). 'Has remembered us' is the past tense of covenant assurance: YHWH's memory of his covenant people is the ground for the future blessing.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'...he will bless those who fear the LORD, both the small and the great'</b> — 'both the small and the great' (<i>haqqetannim im hagedolim</i>) — the blessing is not tiered by social status. The smallest (<i>qatan</i>) and the greatest (<i>gadol</i>) receive the same blessing from the same God. The social leveling of the covenant community: no covenant distinction between ranks of worshiper.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'May the LORD give you increase, you and your children!'</b> — the blessing of multiplication: <i>yoseph YHWH aleichem</i> (may the LORD increase you). The covenant multiplication blessing (Deut 28:4: 'blessed shall be the fruit of your womb') expressed as a Hallel prayer. The inclusion of 'your children' (<i>veal beneichem</i>) extends the blessing intergenerationally.</p>", "15": "<p><b>'May you be blessed by the LORD, who made heaven and earth!'</b> — 'who made heaven and earth' (<i>oseh shamayim vaaretz</i>) — the creator-title as the ground of the blessing. The one who made heaven and earth (all created space) is the one blessing the covenant community. The creator's blessing is guaranteed by his own creative power: he has resources to bless from his own creation.</p>", "16": "<p><b>'The heavens are the LORD's heavens, but the earth he has given to the children of man'</b> — 'the heavens are the LORD's' (<i>hashamayim shamayim laYHWH</i>) — YHWH's domain. 'The earth he has given to the children of man' (<i>vehaaretz natan livnei adam</i>) — the earth as humanity's domain by divine grant. This is the creation-mandate theology of Gen 1:28: YHWH creates, then delegates earth-governance to humans (<i>adam</i>). The distinction between divine and human spheres does not mean divine absence from earth but explains why earth-governance is humanity's responsibility.</p>", "17": "<p><b>'The dead do not praise the LORD, nor do any who go down into silence'</b> — 'the dead do not praise the LORD' (<i>lo hameitim yehalelu Yah</i>) — one of the OT's clearest statements about death and praise. Those who have descended to Sheol (the realm of the dead, 'silence' <i>dumah</i>) cannot participate in the praise of the living community. This is the OT anthropology of the underworld: Sheol is a place of shadows and silence, not of covenant relationship (Pss 6:5; 30:9; 88:10-12; Isa 38:18). The statement creates urgency for the living community: praise now, before death silences the voice.</p>", "18": "<p><b>'But we will bless the LORD from this time forth and forevermore. Praise the LORD!'</b> — the psalm's conclusion turns the urgency of v17 into a vow: 'we will bless the LORD' (<i>vaanachnu nevarech Yah</i>) — the living community taking responsibility for the praise that the dead cannot offer. 'From this time forth and forevermore' (<i>me'atah vead olam</i>) — the same temporal formula as Ps 113:2, creating a bracket within the Egyptian Hallel. The final 'Hallelujah!' closes the anti-idol psalm with the affirmation that YHWH alone is worthy of the praise that idols can neither give nor receive.</p>"}, "116": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 116: Individual Thanksgiving After Deliverance from Death — Setting for the Cup of Salvation.</b> Ps 116 is an individual thanksgiving psalm with an unusually personal and intimate register. The psalmist addresses YHWH directly throughout and narrates his near-death experience and rescue in the first person. The opening is striking: 'I love the LORD' (<i>ahavti ki yishma YHWH et qoli</i>, I love because YHWH heard my voice). The <i>ahav</i> (love) is the relational term of covenant: the same verb used for YHWH's love for Israel (Deut 7:8) now comes from the human side. The ground of love is experiential: YHWH heard my voice — the particular, personal act of hearing.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'Because he inclined his ear to me, therefore I will call on him as long as I live'</b> — 'inclined his ear' (<i>hittah ozno li</i>) — the image of YHWH bending down to listen: the sovereign stooping to hear the petitioner. This posture of divine attention became the ground of the psalmist's lifelong prayer habit: 'therefore I will call on him as long as I live' (<i>uveyamai eqra</i>). The personal experience of answered prayer creates the pattern for all future prayer.</p>", "3": "<p><b>'The snares of death encompassed me; the pangs of Sheol laid hold on me; I suffered distress and anguish'</b> — 'snares of death' (<i>apaphuni chevlei mavet</i>) — the cords or nets of death surrounding the psalmist. 'Pangs of Sheol' (<i>umetzarei she'ol metza'uni</i>) — the anguish of Sheol's distress found him. The language of near-death experience: the psalmist was within Sheol's grasp. The 'pangs' (<i>metzarim</i>, straits/distress) may refer to a severe illness or life-threatening circumstance whose specifics the psalm does not disclose.</p>", "4": "<p><b>'Then I called on the name of the LORD: O LORD, I pray, deliver my soul!'</b> — the rescue cry: 'called on the name of the LORD' (<i>uveshem YHWH eqra</i>) — the divine Name as the address for prayer. 'O LORD, I pray, deliver my soul' (<i>ana YHWH malleta naphshi</i>) — the petition's simplicity: deliver my <i>naphesh</i> (soul/life). The <i>ana</i> (please, I pray) is an urgent petition particle, marking the seriousness of the request.</p>", "5": "<p><b>'Gracious is the LORD, and righteous; our God is merciful'</b> — the theological confession prompted by the rescue: 'gracious' (<i>channun</i>), 'righteous' (<i>tzaddiq</i>), 'merciful' (<i>mrachem</i>). These three divine attributes are not abstract doctrines but experientially verified through the psalmist's rescue. The OT theology of divine character is always grounded in historical experience — the attributes are known through the acts.</p>", "6": "<p><b>'The LORD preserves the simple; when I was brought low, he saved me'</b> — 'preserves the simple' (<i>shomer peta'im YHWH</i>) — the <i>peti</i> (simple one) — the naive, inexperienced person who lacks cunning. The divine protection of the simple/naive is unexpected: YHWH protects those who have the least ability to protect themselves, not those with the greatest skill. 'When I was brought low, he saved me' (<i>daloti veli yehoshia</i>) — the poverty-rescue pattern: at the nadir of weakness, YHWH acts.</p>", "7": "<p><b>'Return, O my soul, to your rest; for the LORD has dealt bountifully with you'</b> — 'return to your rest' (<i>shuvi naphshi limenuchayichi</i>) — the psalmist addresses his own soul, calling it back to its covenant resting place. The <i>menuchah</i> (rest) — the covenant rest that was disturbed by the near-death crisis — is restored. 'The LORD has dealt bountifully with you' (<i>ki YHWH gamal alaichi</i>) — <i>gamal</i> (to deal bountifully, to ripen, to wean): the word covers the full process of bringing something to completion and fullness. YHWH has brought the psalmist's experience to a full and good conclusion.</p>", "8": "<p><b>'For you have delivered my soul from death, my eyes from tears, my feet from stumbling'</b> — the three-part rescue: from death (<i>mavet</i>), from tears (<i>dim'ah</i>), from stumbling (<i>dochi</i>). The rescue is comprehensive: not just physical survival but the removal of grief and the restoration of stable walking. The three are a descending scale: from the ultimate danger (death) to the emotional response (tears) to the physical instability (stumbling). YHWH addressed all three levels.</p>", "9": "<p><b>'I will walk before the LORD in the land of the living'</b> — 'walk before the LORD' (<i>ethalech lifnei YHWH</i>) — the covenant walk in YHWH's presence (Gen 17:1: 'walk before me and be blameless'). 'In the land of the living' (<i>beartzot hachayim</i>) — the phrase contrasts with the realm of the dead (Sheol, the land of silence): the psalmist will live, not die, and his living will be a covenant walk in YHWH's presence.</p>", "10": "<p><b>'I believed, even when I spoke: I am greatly afflicted'</b> — Paul quotes this verse in 2 Cor 4:13 ('I believed, and so I spoke') as the paradigm of apostolic faith: belief that speaks even under suffering. The original context: the psalmist maintained faith (<i>he'emanti</i>, perfect: I have believed) even while confessing affliction (<i>ani anitiy meod</i>, I am greatly afflicted). Faith does not require silence about suffering; the Psalms model the co-existence of belief and lament.</p>", "11": "<p><b>'I said in my alarm, All men are liars'</b> — 'in my alarm' (<i>vani amarti vechapzi</i>, in my haste/panic) — the emotional state of crisis producing an overgeneralization: 'all men are liars' (<i>kol haadam kozev</i>). The panic-statement is neither endorsed nor condemned by the psalm — it is honestly reported as what was said in extremity. The contrast between the panic-confession (v11) and the covenant-walk resolution (v9) shows the range of human experience within authentic faith.</p>", "12": "<p><b>'What shall I render to the LORD for all his benefits to me?'</b> — the question of reciprocity: <i>mah ashiv laYHWH</i> (what shall I return to YHWH?). 'His benefits' (<i>kol tagmulohi</i>, all his dealings/benefits toward me) — the <i>gamal</i> root again (cf. v7). The psalmist's question is not rhetorical despair but genuine reflection: given everything YHWH has done, what appropriate response is there? The answer follows in the next verses.</p>", "13": "<p><b>'I will lift up the cup of salvation and call on the name of the LORD'</b> — 'the cup of salvation' (<i>kos yeshu'ot essa</i>) — the specific vessel of the <i>todah</i> (thanksgiving sacrifice): the cup of wine raised in the thanksgiving ceremony in the temple courts. The 'cup' imagery has a rich trajectory: the cup of blessing in the Passover seder (the third cup was the 'cup of blessing,' cf. 1 Cor 10:16) and ultimately the Eucharist cup of the new covenant. The cup of salvation is raised and the divine name called on — public testimony accompanying the libation.</p>", "14": "<p><b>'I will pay my vows to the LORD in the presence of all his people'</b> — 'pay my vows' (<i>nedarai laYHWH ashalem</i>) — the vow made in distress (v4: 'I pray, deliver my soul') is fulfilled publicly. 'In the presence of all his people' (<i>negdah na lekhol amo</i>) — the public fulfillment in the temple assembly. The ANE vow-system required public fulfillment before the community: the covenant community witnessed the transaction between worshiper and YHWH.</p>", "15": "<p><b>'Precious in the sight of the LORD is the death of his saints'</b> — 'precious' (<i>yaqar</i>, costly, valued, rare) — 'the death of his saints' (<i>hamaveta lahasidav</i>) is precious to YHWH. The verse is the most-quoted in Christian funeral liturgy and is interpreted in two ways: (1) YHWH does not allow his saints to die lightly or needlessly — their deaths are 'costly' to him, treated with great care; (2) YHWH values the death of his faithful as something that comes at high cost and is not easily conceded. Neither interpretation makes death desirable but both affirm divine attentiveness to the deaths of covenant people.</p>", "16": "<p><b>'O LORD, I am your servant; I am your servant, the son of your maidservant. You have loosed my bonds'</b> — 'I am your servant' (<i>ani avdechah</i>) — double identification as <i>eved</i> (servant). 'The son of your maidservant' (<i>ben amatchah</i>) — born into the divine household: the son of a maidservant was a permanent, household servant (unlike a purchased slave who might be freed). 'You have loosed my bonds' (<i>pittachta lemoseirai</i>) — the rescue from the near-death 'bonds' of vv3-4 is now described as liberation. The servant who was bound is now freed — still a servant, but no longer in death's bonds.</p>", "17": "<p><b>'I will offer to you the sacrifice of thanksgiving and call on the name of the LORD'</b> — 'sacrifice of thanksgiving' (<i>zevach todah</i>) — the specific sacrificial category (Lev 7:12-15): a peace-offering accompanied by leavened and unleavened bread, eaten on the day of offering, requiring the whole household and invited guests. The <i>todah</i> (thanksgiving/confession) sacrifice was the OT ceremony of public gratitude after deliverance. The <i>todah</i> connection to the Eucharist is deeply rooted: Jesus's Last Supper in the Passover context used Hallel psalms that include <i>todah</i> language.</p>", "18": "<p><b>'I will pay my vows to the LORD in the presence of all his people'</b> — the refrain from v14 repeated, creating a structural bracket. The double statement of public vow-fulfillment (vv14,18) emphasizes the communal, non-private nature of covenant gratitude. Individual rescue produces communal testimony. The vow paid in public before 'all his people' is the psalm's answer to the question of v12.</p>", "19": "<p><b>'...in the courts of the house of the LORD, in your midst, O Jerusalem. Praise the LORD!'</b> — 'the courts of the house of the LORD' (<i>bechatzerot beit YHWH</i>) — the specific location: the temple courts where the <i>todah</i> sacrifice was offered and where the vow-fulfillment would be witnessed. 'In your midst, O Jerusalem' (<i>betocheki Yerushalaim</i>) — the city is addressed directly; the testimony of rescue takes place in the capital of the covenant community. The 'Hallelujah' closes the psalm, sending the testimony outward from the individual thanksgiving to universal praise.</p>"}, "117": {"1": "<p><b>Ps 117: The Shortest Chapter in the Bible — Universal Praise, Covenantal Ground.</b> Ps 117 is both the shortest chapter in the Bible (2 verses) and the chapter closest to the Bible's midpoint. Its brevity belies its theological density: in two verses it encompasses universal scope (all nations, all peoples), covenant ground (<i>chesed</i> and <i>emet</i>), and eternal duration ('forever'). Paul cites this psalm in Rom 15:11 as one of four OT texts establishing that Gentiles were always intended to glorify God — the nations praising YHWH is not a NT innovation but a Psalter expectation. 'Praise the LORD, all nations! Extol him, all peoples!' (<i>hallelu et YHWH kol goyim shabechuhu kol haumim</i>) — the imperative extends to 'all nations' (<i>kol goyim</i>) and 'all peoples' (<i>kol haumim</i>). These are universal terms; no nation is excluded from the summons to praise YHWH.</p>", "2": "<p><b>'For great is his steadfast love toward us, and the faithfulness of the LORD endures forever. Praise the LORD!'</b> — the grounds for universal praise: YHWH's <i>chesed</i> (steadfast love) 'toward us' (<i>alenu</i>) — the primary recipients are Israel, but the praise is universal. The paradox of Ps 117: the nations are called to praise YHWH because of what he has done for Israel. The particularity of the covenant (YHWH's <i>chesed</i> toward Israel) produces the universality of the praise. 'The faithfulness of the LORD endures forever' (<i>ve-emet YHWH leolam</i>) — the same <i>emet</i> (faithfulness) that appeared in Ps 111-116 closes the Egyptian Hallel's penultimate psalm with the eternal divine attribute. The 'Hallelujah' at the close opens into Ps 118.</p>"}}

if __name__ == '__main__':
    book = 'psalms'
    source = 'mkt-context'
    existing = load_comm(source, book)
    merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
    save_comm(source, book, existing)
    for ch, vv in NEW_DATA.items():
        saved = existing.get(ch, {})
        missing = [v for v in vv if v not in saved]
        print(f'  ch {ch}: {len(vv)} entries, {len(missing)} missing after merge')
